  <p>For most of us, the experience of “going to work” tends to be a steady, predictable, and more-or-less mandatory part of life. The traditional office job has evolved certain indelible qualities over the past 60 years or so. We commute in and out. We sit in chairs. We work on computers. We deal with co-workers. Meetings are convened. They are interminable. Coffee is often involved.</p>

  <p><a href="https://revisesociology.com/2016/08/16/percentage-life-work/">Recent studies</a> suggest that we will spend about one-quarter to one-third of our lives like this. Plenty of different factors inform the work environment, of course – location, compensation, bosses. But one variable is changing things rapidly in the 21st century – technology. For the traditional office job, anyway, available technology of the day determines a great deal of the overall work experience.</p>

  <p>Here we look at several emerging technologies that are likely to impact the work world in coming years. There are a lot of different jobs out there, so to keep things manageable, we're focusing in on the typical office scenario. We're also calibrating the time machine to scan just the near-future possibilities – the next 20 years or so. These technologies are in various stages of development – some are in the research labs, others may be in your office right now. Some are incredible. Some are goofy. And some are a little spooky. Let's punch the clock.</p>

  <h3 class="crosshed">The Commute</h3>
