  <p>For urban folk who rely on public transportation, the work commute has gradually shifted in recent decades with the advent of the laptop computer, the smart phone, and wireless Internet access. Lots of us now find ourselves working while we're commuting, on the subway, train or bus.</p>

  <p>We may soon be working in our cars, too. Autonomous vehicle technology is moving very quickly, and some forward-thinking companies are already designing self-driving cars that essentially function as mobile offices. Set your destination, flip a switch, and the interior of the car morphs into an office configuration: The driver's seat swivels around, desks pop out of the floor, side windows turn into electronic displays. This isn't just sketchbook noodling, either: These next-generation vehicles are already <a href="http://www.vw.com/electric-concepts/section/id-buzz/">in the pipeline</a>.</p>

  <p>A little farther down the development track, several automakers are now designing concept vehicles like the <a href="https://newsroom.toyota.co.jp/en/corporate/20546438.html">Honda e-Palette</a>, pictured above, which can serve as multi-purpose “rooms on wheels” for a full-service office-to-office commute.</p>

