  <p>Of all the emerging technologies likely to impact the typical office job, one in particular is leading the pack just now. Speech recognition has made enormous leaps in recent years. Just ask your Amazon Alexa or Apple Siri. No, really. Go ahead and ask them. There's a reason that the planet's largest tech companies are investing so heavily in this stuff.</p>

  <p>Hundreds of major speech-recognition initiatives are now in development across all industries. The technology represents a fundamental shift in how we interact with computers, which is usually the central activity in most office jobs. The emerging consensus is that, in the next 10-20 years, speech recognition will supplant the keyboard as our primary of communicating with our various machines.</p>

  <p>The idea isn't all that new, actually. Veterans of the personal computer revolution can tell you that workplace speech recognition tech has actually been around since the 1990s. Alas, to indulge in industry jargon, it has traditionally sucked. The surprising accuracy of today's systems is due almost entirely to recent advances in machine learning and artificial intelligence, plus better microphones.</p>

