  <p>As we think up new ways to interact with our workplace machines, you can expect a lot of crossover into that sprawling area of technology known as virtual reality. For instance, gesture recognition is just one aspect of a much larger effort to demolish the boundaries between physical space and virtual space. Will the day ever arrive where the physical office is replaced by the virtual office?</p>

  <p>In some fast-forward workplaces, it's already arrived. Ford Motor Company is currently operating several research labs that are essentially virtual reality offices. At facilities in Michigan, California, Germany and China, engineers spend most of their time strapped into VR headsets. They may be physically sitting in Michigan or Germany, but the real workplace is the <a href="http://driving.ca/ford/auto-news/news/how-it-works-ford-design-studios">Ford Vehicle Immersion Environment</a> (FiVE), a virtual reality construct where designers collaborate on immersive 3D models of concept vehicles. In this virtual office space, physical distance is irrelevant and engineers on different continents work side by side.</p>

  <p>Such collaborative VR workplaces are popping up all over the place in manufacturing, and in other industries as well. Virtual reality is such a complex and fast-moving technology that it's tricky to generate any useful prognostication. But based on the money and resources being poured into the field, many more office workers will be strapping on goggles and gloves in the not-so-distant future.</p>

