  <p>Back here on the grubby non-virtual plane, we must still contend with the physical environs of the workplace. Entire segments of the retail furniture business are dedicated to selling you on the tables and chairs and office décor of the near future – your standing desks and ergonomic smart chairs. But what will the true next-generation office look like?</p>

  <p>One intriguing vision of the future office was recently on display in Holland. <a href="http://www.raaaf.nl/en/projects/927_the_end_of_sitting/951">The End of Sitting</a> is an experimental installation that imagines a future office space of dynamic geometries and surfaces. A collaboration between artist Barbara Visser and the design studio Rietveld Architecture-Art-Affordances (RAAAF), the project is an attempt to radically rethink the office paradigm; “to develop a concept wherein the chair and desk are no longer unquestionable starting points.”</p>

  <p>Click around online and you can find <a href="https://www.businessnewsdaily.com/9463-smart-office-responsive-workplace.html">similar concepts</a> from forward-thinking design groups. Much of this work has been spurred by mounting <a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-lifestyle/adult-health/expert-answers/sitting/faq-20058005">scientific evidence</a> that sitting all day is decidedly unhealthy. Can't argue with that.</p>

