  <p>Artificial intelligence represents a global workplace upheaval so potentially massive that it's hard to even introduce without spraining a frontal lobe. The same with the advanced robotic systems that are displacing human workers all over the planet. Emerging consensus suggests that these two interrelated technologies will have the most profound impact in the next 20 years – not just in the workplace, but for our species as a whole.</p>

  <p>Click around online and you can find all sorts of scary statistics. An oft-cited <a href="https://www.pwc.co.uk/economic-services/ukeo/pwcukeo-section-4-automation-march-2017-v2.pdf">2017 study</a> by the consulting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers suggests that more than a third of U.S. jobs are at “high risk” of becoming fully automated by the year 2030. <a href="https://www.mckinsey.com/featured-insights/digital-disruption/harnessing-automation-for-a-future-that-works">More optimistic studies</a> predict that other market forces will offset these losses; that the very nature of our economy will change, as it did during the Industrial Revolution.</p>

  <p>How will all these seismic forces inform the experience of going to work? The awful truth is that no one knows. You can find some genuinely <a href="http://theinstitute.ieee.org/ns/quarterly_issues/tijun16.pdf">good primers</a> on the topic, but this is an adventure we're all going on together, sooner than later, and without a map. As always – there's no substitute for experience.</p>


